    "Alfred Edersheim": "ver. 14), that during its course David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s headquarters were on \u201cmountain heights,\u201d fm18 whence he could easily observe the approach of an enemy, while \u201cSaul sought him every day,\u201d but in vain, since \u201cGod gave him not into his hand.\u201d The first station in these wanderings was the \u201cwilderness of Ziph,\u201d on the outskirts of the town of that name, about an hour and three-quarters to the south-east of Hebron. South of it a solitary mountain-top rises about one hundred feet, commanding a full prospect of the surrounding country. On the other hand, anything that passed there could also easily be observed from below. It seems that this was \u201cthe mountain\u201d (\nver. 14), or, as it is afterwards (\nver. 14), \u201cone to a hundred the least, and the greatest one to a thousand,\u201d who when breaking away from the army of Saul had not only crossed Jordan in the dangerous floodtime of early spring, but cut their way through those who would have barred it (",
