    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And make ye marriages with us, etc.] There was no objection on their side, it lay on the other; Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`\u2019s servant was charged by him not to take a wife of the Canaanites to his son Isaac; and the same charge was [v_Gen_24_3] given Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` by Isaac, (<012403>Genesis 24:3 28:1); and therefore Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` would never agree that his children should marry any of that nation; and marriages with them were afterwards forbidden by the law of Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`, [v_Deu_7_3] (<050703>Deuteronomy 7:3); [and] give your daughters unto us, and take our daughters unto you; for though at present there were no other daughters in Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`\u2019s family, yet there might be hereafter; and the request is, that for the future there might be intermarriages between them, as would be practicable in a course of time.\nVer.\n9. What is the uniform method of historic treatment in the book of Genesis?",
    "Commentary Vol. 84": "What present did he send Esau and what was the plan of presentation?"
